Malaysian Economic and Agriculture Price 2019 Prediction

Valentina Zhong (63260335)

31/03/2022

Background: Malaysia in 2018

This analysis draws inspiration and data from previous work performed by Mohaddes & Raissi (2020) in which economic data along with industry indicators are studied to forecast futures values. The intent of this analysis is to understand and explain the economic situation within the country of Malaysia while giving attention to the agriculture sector to forecast 2019 values. The chosen country of interest, Malaysia, was selected because of its unique position as an economy transitioning from upper-middle income to high income. The Southeast Asian country boasted a population of 32.4 million in 2018 with a GDP per capita of $11,380.82 (Current $USD) (Mahidin, 2019b, World Bank, 2022). This level of income makes it one of the wealthiest countries in Southeast Asia. This analysis will investigate and forecast the agriculture sector in addition to the economic indicators provided within the dataset.

Dataset

  • University of Cambridge Global VAR (GVAR) Database, 1979Q2-2019Q4

Roadmap

Based on a time series dataset, we will apply different time series models to predict the economic performance and agriculture price in 2019. The analysis mainly develop into three parts. Stationary is one of the most important assumptions for time series modelling. Therefore, we start from the stationary test before model specification. During the model construction, the data will be divided into two groups, which are training set and testing set. To evaluate the accuracy of models, accuracy matrix will be designed, where there are different type of error terms. After the accuracy analysis, several model characteristic will be examined, which include series correlation and heteroskedasticity.

Stationary Analysis on the Whole Dataset

data <- read_excel(here("data","Data.xlsx"))

data$date <- as.Date(as.yearqtr(data$date, format = "%YQ%q"))
# y <- natural logarithm of real GDP
# Dp <- the rate of inflation, calculated by taking the difference of the natural logarithm of the consumer price index
# eq <- natural logarithm of the nominal equity price index deflated by CPI
# ep <- natural logarithm of the exchange rate of country i at time t expressed in US dollars deflated by country i's eq
# r <- nominal short-term interest rate per quarter, in per cent
# lr <- nominal long-term interest rate per quarter, in per cent (computed as 0.25ln(1+ /100)) <- we do not have
# pmat <- natural logarithm of the nominal price of agricultural raw material in US dollars

data <- data %>%
  mutate(lngdp = as.numeric(y),
         inflat = as.numeric(Dp),
         lneq = as.numeric(eq),
         lnex = as.numeric(ep),
         r = as.numeric(r),
         agri = as.numeric(pmat))%>%
  dplyr::select(date,lngdp,inflat,lneq,lnex,r,agri)

# set cutoff date for training and validation (test) periods
cutoff_date = "2018-10-01"

# 2. Creating training and forecasting datasets
## 2.1 Training dataset

  filter(data$date <= cutoff_date)

## 2. Forecasting dataset
data_set_fore <- data %>% filter(data$date > cutoff_date)

fore_period <- nrow(data_set_fore)

Conclusion

We proceeded to perform a VAR(2) model, to do so we first tested stationarity, and after testing Augmented Dickey Fuller, we have found that inflation was the only stationary variable, therefore we applied first differences to the rest of the variables to make them stationary, and that way include them in the VAR as the theory suggests.

Besides, a Nave-Random Walk model and ARIMA- Univariate model were performed as the benchmark models to assess, with the comparison of RMSE, which model fitted better. Only in the GDP, we found that the ARIMA RMSE was slightly better, other than that, the VAR model outperformed the ARIMA and NAVE, both in the training and the test set. This was confirmed with the RMSE Ratio, where all the ratios were far from 1, showing that we are far from a random walk model. However, when performing the Diebold Mariano, we found that we can reject the null of the two models are not statistically different for Equity, Exchange Rate and Interest Rate. These results caught our attention and further exploration should be done, especially this could be the case of the forecasted period and a specific behaviour in this phase.

Finally, we would like to acknowledge the importance these macroeconomic forecasts given that we are making monetary decision based on the performance of these variables, all economic agents are involved in the results of these projection, from the GDP growth impacting politicians decisions, inflation and interest rate affecting the consumers behaviours, Equity prices and exchange rate affecting the investors decision, and finally, the agricultural price index affecting the behaviours of the farmers and even a worldwide trend given that Malaysia is the second largest palm oil exporter, which could impact the world dynamics.
